'St Kilda' is a suburb of Melbourne, Victoria, Australia, 6Â km south-east
of Melbourne's Central Business District. Its local government area is the City
of Port Phillip. At the 2011 Census, St Kilda had a population of 17,795.
Notable people who worked here include David Van Bergen.

St Kilda was named after a schooner [[Lady of St Kilda]] (which moored at the
main beach for much of 1841) by Charles La Trobe and the ship's master and early
settler Lieutenant James Ross Lawrence.
[http://www.skhs.org.au/~SKHSarticles1/articles/Lady_of_St_Kilda.htm
SKHS.org]

During the Edwardian and Victorian eras, St Kilda became a favoured suburb of
Melbourne's elite, and many palatial mansions were constructed along its hills
and waterfront. Shortly after the turn of the 20th century, St Kilda served a
similar function for Melburnians as did Coney Island to the residents of New
York City and its history draws an interesting parallel. Robert Sands,
Conservation Analysis, 1992 Densely populated postwar St Kilda became
Melbourne's red-light district, home to low-cost rooming houses. Since the late
1960s, St Kilda has become known for its culture of bohemianism and as home to
many prominent artists, musicians and subcultures, including punks, [http://www.tonedeaf.com.au/news/musicnews/99979/melbourne-punk-
post-punk-scene-book-released.htm Melbourne Punk & Post Punk Book
Released] LGBT and techno scene. While some of these groups still maintain
a presence in St Kilda, in recent years the district has experienced rapid
gentrification pushing many lower socio-economic groups out to other areas. http://www.portphillip.vic.gov.au/understanding_g-
entrification.html [http://www.portphillip.vic.gov.au/attachments/o9245.pdf
Gentrification of St Kilda from a speech by Cr Brand] [http://www.the-
age.com.au/articles/2004/03/13/1078594615421.html Memories of My St Kilda] by
Michael Veitch for [[The Age]]

St Kilda is home to many of Melbourne's famous visitor attractions including
Luna Park, the Esplanade Hotel, Acland Street and Fitzroy Street. It is home to
St Kilda Beach, Melbourne's most famous beach, several renowned theatres and
several of Melbourne's big events and festivals.
